4) Why this will be “extremely fast” in your architecture

Runtime optimizer selection is a single switch(enum) (no string compares inside the loop).

Your callback is invoked exactly once per iteration/generation, and history is stored in your existing HistoryStore (same as DE).

ADAM update is fast; the dominant cost is gradient estimation. SPSA keeps it at 2 objective calls per SPSA sample per iteration (not O(dim) like finite-diff). That’s the only realistic way to make Adam viable for your objective without rewriting it for autodiff.

5) One critical reality check (so you don’t chase ghosts)

Even with “fast Adam”, if you set:

samples = 1..2, Adam will be very fast but noisier.

samples = 4..8, it will be more stable but slower.

Your objective itself is not smooth (min/max/overlap penalties), so Adam will never behave like it does for smooth ML loss functions. With SPSA it can still work well, but GA/DE will usually be more robust for this kind of landscape.
